<fig id="undfig1" position="float" orientation="portrait"><graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" position="float" orientation="portrait" xlink:href="fx1.jpg"><?image-name fx1.jpg?><?image-size 276821?><?image-md5 b49b58144e1aa922ca32f7a21602efb9?><?image-image-server-status NEVER_LOAD?><?image-original-height 515?><?image-original-width 490?><?image-scaled-height 515?><?image-scaled-width 490?><?image-cloudpmc-urn urn:cdn:blobs/a8cd/13131419/b49b58144e1a/fx1.jpg?><?thumb-name fx1.gif?><?thumb-size 79242?><?thumb-md5 35a960ac44faa98931bd52d86e036ad9?><?thumb-image-server-status NEVER_LOAD?><?thumb-scaled-height 105?><?thumb-scaled-width 100?><?thumb-cloudpmc-urn urn:cdn:blobs/a8cd/13131419/35a960ac44fa/fx1.gif?></graphic></fig>
</p><p id="p0015">Time flies—my first 6 months at the helm of <italic toggle="yes">JACC: Basic to Translational Science</italic> are already behind me. Last summer, after toiling as an author for a quarter of a century, I answered a call to serve and began changing sides—at least for part of the day—when logging onto the journal’s website as its Editor-in-Chief. My motivation for accepting this role was to channel some of the pain I experienced during peer review as an author into meaningful improvements for our scientific community.</p><p id="p0020">My journey has only just begun, and I am grateful that I am not traveling it alone. One of the greatest rewards associated with this new role has been working with our outstanding editorial board—esteemed colleagues who agreed to join me and whom I now have the pleasure of meeting with every week. Thank you for your dedication and service, Andrew Lewis, Aneesh Bapat, Cameron McAlpine, Daniela Carnevale, Gustavo Ramos, Jason Roh, Kory Lavine, Maarten Hulsmanns, Nick Frangogiannis, and Sabine Steffens. I am also especially grateful to Kimberly Trevey (Managing Editor) and Monica Payne-Emmerson (Executive Managing Editor), who have ensured that the new board quickly found its footing and who keep us on track.</p><p id="p0025">Together, we strive hard to make <italic toggle="yes">JACC: Basic to Translational Science</italic> an appealing venue for scientific discourse. We have broadened the journal’s scope to welcome all basic science papers addressing cardiovascular and neurovascular disease, as well as related work in hematology and immunology. We are committed to improving our interactions with authors and to providing faster, more collegial decisions. One particularly successful initiative has been the fast-track pathway for papers previously rejected elsewhere. We typically accept such submissions very quickly and without another round of external review. Please reach out if you have questions about this submission track. I am also eager to hear your general feedback and your ideas how we can do better—after all, I see my role as an Editor-in-Chief as service to you: our readers, authors, and reviewers.</p><p id="p0030">The journal would be nothing without its diligent reviewers, who tirelessly help select and improve the papers we publish. At a time when some aspects of science have become big business, it is all the more remarkable that busy academics continue to volunteer their time and expertise. A heartfelt thank you to all of our reviewers and especially to our top reviewers of 2025:</p><p id="p0035">DiyaaEldin Ashour</p><p id="p0040">Mario Enrico Canonico</p><p id="p0045">Ali J. Marian</p><p id="p0050">Stanley Nattel</p><p id="p0055">Jan Nilsson</p><p id="p0060">Harvey Roweth</p><p id="p0065">Yibin Wang</p><p id="p0070">Antonio Abbate</p><p id="p0075">Michael Bauer</p><p id="p0080">Darren E. Casteel</p><p id="p0085">Charles S. Chung</p><p id="p0090">Gianluigi Condorelli</p><p id="p0095">Annarita Di Lorenzo</p><p id="p0100">Konstantinos Drosatos</p><p id="p0105">Nicola Ferri</p><p id="p0110">Andrew A. Gibb</p><p id="p0115">Peter Hanna</p><p id="p0120">Kevin D. Hill</p><p id="p0125">Zamaneh Kassiri</p><p id="p0130">Regent Lee</p><p id="p0135">Together, reviewers and editors curate the content of <italic toggle="yes">JACC: Basic to Translational Science</italic>, ensuring that the journal remains a core contributor to cardiovascular science and evolves in step with a fast-paced research environment. Our goal is to be among the most engaging and impactful venues in the field and to inspire our readers.</p><p id="p0140">Our most-read papers of 2025 exemplify this ambition:<list list-type="simple" id="ulist0010"><list-item id="u0010"><label>•</label><p id="p0145"><italic toggle="yes">Recent Pathophysiological Insights Are Advancing the Treatment of Venous Thromboembolism</italic><xref rid="bib1" ref-type="bibr"><sup>1</sup></xref></p></list-item><list-item id="u0015"><label>•</l